{"title_page": "Ted McKeever", "text_new": "{{short description|American comic artist}}\n{{Infobox comics creator\n| name = Ted McKeever\n| image = \n| imagesize = 150\n| caption = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = [[United States|American]]\n| cartoonist = \n| write = y\n| art = \n| pencil = y\n| ink = y\n| edit = \n| publish = \n| letter = y\n| color = \n| alias = \n| notable works = {{ubl|''[[Plastic Forks]]''|''[[Metropol (comics)|Metropol]]''|''Perpetual Mourning'' (''[[Batman: Black & White]]'' #1)}}\n| awards = \n| website = {{official}}\n| sortkey = Mackeever, Ted\n| subcat = American\n}}\n'''Ted McKeever''' is an American [[comic]]s artist and author.\n\n==Career==\nMcKeever first professional work appeared in 1987, when he published the first five parts of his unfinished series ''Transit'' ([[Vortex Comics]]), establishing his trademark style. This was followed in 1987\u20131988 by his 12-part series ''[[Eddy Current (comics)|Eddy Current]]''. This \"12-hour book\" centers on an escapee from an asylum. Obsessed with the exploits of the superhero \"The Amazing Broccoli,\" Eddy buys a mail-order battery-powered \"Dynamic Fusion Suit\" and sets out to save the world. The work is quintessential McKeever: darkly humorous, showing an \"ordinary\" person caught up in extraordinary events. Some of the characters in Eddy Current reappear in ''Metropol'' and other later works, similarly from ''Transit''.  This series was nominated for the [[Eisner Award]]s for Best Single-Issue (#1), Best Black-and-White Series, Best New Series, and Best Artist (for McKeever) for 1988.\n\nHis five-parter ''Plastic Forks'' ([[Epic Comics|Epic]], 1990) explored the world of animal experimentation, albeit in a surreal and comical way.\n\n''Metropol'' ([[Epic Comics|Epic]] 1991\u20131992) is an epic story of the fight between angels and demons, but set in a modern  industrial landscape. An apocalyptic work in which non-entity Jasper Notochord becomes involved in a surreal fight between the forces of good and evil.\n\n''The Extremist'' ([[Vertigo Comics|Vertigo]], 1993), a four-parter written by [[Peter Milligan]], tells the tale of a woman who finds that her husband had a secret life, which she discovers upon his death. Her investigations lead her into a shocking world of extreme sex and violence.<ref name=\"vert-extr\">{{Citation  | last = Irvine | first = Alex | author-link = Alexander C. Irvine | contribution = The Extremist | editor-last = Dougall  | editor-first = Alastair  | title = The Vertigo Encyclopedia  | pages = 71 | publisher = [[Dorling Kindersley]]  | place = New York  | year = 2008 | ISBN = 0-7566-4122-5 | oclc = 213309015}}</ref>\n\nMcKeever has produced a number of works exploring alternative realities within the world of [[DC Comics|DC]] superhero comics. With Randy & [[Jean-Marc Lofficier]], he has produced an [[Elseworlds]] trilogy: ''[[Superman's Metropolis]]'', ''[[Batman: Nosferatu]]''\nand ''[[Wonder Woman: The Blue Amazon]]'', all retellings of the DC mythos.\n\nIn addition to Milligan and Randy & Jean-Marc Lofficier, McKeever has collaborated with comics creators [[Dave Gibbons]] and writer and singer [[Lydia Lunch]]. ''Enginehead'' (DC, 2004), was written by [[Joe Kelly (comics)|Joe Kelly]].\n\nIn 2010 McKeever worked on a five-part series titled \"Meta4\" for [[Image Comics]] where he has since published his recent projects for [[Jim Valentino]]'s Shadowline imprint.\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n* 1988 [[Eisner Award]]<ref name=\"awards-eisner-88\">{{Citation\n| last = Hahn\n| first = Joel\n| title = 1988 Will Eisner Comic Industry Award Nominees\n| url = http://www.hahnlibrary.net/comics/awards/eisner88.php\n| accessdate = 2008-10-19\n}}</ref>\n** Best Single Issue nominee: ''[[Eddy Current (comics)|Eddy Current]]'' #1\n** Best Black-and-White Series nominee: ''[[Eddy Current (comics)|Eddy Current]]''\n** Best New Series nominee: ''[[Eddy Current (comics)|Eddy Current]]''\n** Best Artist nominee: ''[[Eddy Current (comics)|Eddy Current]]''\n* 1991 [[Eisner Award]]<ref name=\"awards-eisner-91\">{{Citation\n| last = Hahn\n| first = Joel\n| title = 1991 Will Eisner Comic Industry Award Nominees and Winners\n| url = http://www.hahnlibrary.net/comics/awards/eisner91.php\n| accessdate = 2008-10-19\n}}</ref>\n** Best Artist nominee\n* 1992 Harvey Award<ref name=\"awards-harvey-92\">{{Citation\n| last = Hahn\n| first = Joel\n| title = 1992 Harvey Award Nominees and Winners\n| url = http://www.hahnlibrary.net/comics/awards/harvey92.php\n| accessdate = 2008-10-19\n}}</ref>\n** Best Colorist nominee: ''Metropol''\n* 1997 [[Eisner Award]]<ref name=\"awards-eisner-97\">{{Citation\n| last = Hahn\n| first = Joel\n| title = 1997 Will Eisner Comic Industry Award Nominees and Winners\n| url = http://www.hahnlibrary.net/comics/awards/eisner97.php\n| accessdate = 2008-10-19\n}}</ref>\n** Best Short Story nominee: ''Perpetual Mourning'', ''[[Batman: Black & White]]'' #1\n\n==Bibliography==\nComics written and drawn (unless noted otherwise) by Ted McKeever include:\n* ''Transit'' #1\u20135 ([[Vortex Comics|Vortex]], 1987\u20131988 \u2014 previously unfinished, but now completed in 2008 HC released by [[Shadowline]])\n* \"Eddy Current\" (''[[Eddy Current (comics)|Eddy Current]]'' prologue, in ''Splat!'' #3, ''Mad Dog Graphics'', 1987) \n* ''[[Eddy Current (comics)|Eddy Current]]'' #1\u201312 (''Mad Dog Graphics'', 1987\u20131988)\n* \"New Act\" (Eddy Current featured in Munden's Bar Back-up story, in ''[[Grimjack]]'' #47, [[First Comics]], 1988)\n* \"Judgement\" (''[[Eddy Current (comics)|Eddy Current]]'''s Nun short story, in ''[[Escape (magazine)|Escape]]'' #16, [[Titan Books]], 1988 \u2013 reprinted in ''[[A1 (comics)|A1]] [[The Bojeffries Saga|Bojeffries]] Terror Tome'' #1, [[Atomeka Press|Atomeka]], 2005)\n* \"Fish Sticks\" (written by [[Steve Moncuse]], in ''[[Fish Police]]'' vol. 2 #8, [[Comico: The Comic Company|Comico]], 1988)\n* \"Dance of The Fetus\" (in ''[[Hellraiser (comics)|Clive Barker's Hellraiser]]'' #1, [[Epic Comics|Epic]], 1989)\n* \"Libretto\" (art by [[Dave Gibbons]], in ''[[A1 (comics)|A1]] #1, [[Atomeka Press|Atomeka]], 1989)\n* \"Survivor\" (written by [[Dave Gibbons]], in ''[[A1 (comics)|A1]] #1, [[Atomeka Press|Atomeka]], 1989)\n* \"The Talk Of Creatures\" (in ''[[A1 (comics)|A1]] #2, [[Atomeka Press|Atomeka]], 1989)\n* ''Ted McKeever\u2019s [[Plastic Forks]]'' #1\u20135 ([[Epic Comics|Epic]], 1990)\n* ''[[Metropol (comics)|Metropol]]'' #1\u201312 ([[Epic Comics|Epic]], 1991\u20131992)\n* ''Metropol A.D.'' #1\u20133 ([[Epic Comics|Epic]], 1993)\n* ''[[Eclipso]]'' #7\u20138 (written by [[Keith Giffen]] and [[Robert Loren Fleming]], [[DC Comics|DC]], 1993)\n* ''[[The Extremist (comics)|The Extremist]]'' #1\u20134 (written by [[Peter Milligan]], [[Vertigo Comics|Vertigo]], 1993)\n* \"The Creeper: A Cold Night In Hell\" (written by [[Keith Giffen]], in ''Showcase '93'' #12, DC, 1993)\n* ''[[Doom Patrol]]'' #75\u201379, 81\u201382, 84\u201387 (written by [[Rachel Pollack]], [[Vertigo Comics|Vertigo]], 1994\u20131995)\n* ''[[Industrial Gothic]]'' #1\u20135 ([[Vertigo Comics|Vertigo]], 1995)\n* \"Engines\" (in ''[[Legends of the Dark Knight]]'' #74\u201375, DC, 1996)\n* \"Perpetual Mourning\" (in ''[[Batman: Black & White]]'' #1, DC, 1997)\n* ''[[Superman's Metropolis]]'' (written by Randy & [[Jean-Marc Lofficier]] & [[Roy Thomas]], [[Elseworlds]], 1997)\n* ''Junk Culture'' #1\u20132 (DC, 1997)\n* ''Toxic Gumbo'' (written by [[Lydia Lunch]], DC, 1998)\n* ''[[Batman: Nosferatu]]'' (written by Randy & [[Jean-Marc Lofficier]], [[Elseworlds]], 1999)\n* ''[[Faith (Vertigo)|Faith]]'' #1\u20135 ([[Vertigo Comics|Vertigo]], 2000)\n* \"Grave Wisdom\" (in ''[[Flinch (comics)|Flinch]]'' #14, [[Vertigo Comics|Vertigo]], 2000)\n* ''[[Vertigo Comics|Vertigo]] Visions'' ([[Titan Books]], 2000)\n* ''[[Spider-Man's Tangled Web]]'' #18 ([[Marvel Comics|Marvel]], 2002)\n* ''[[Ultimate Marvel Team-Up]]'' #12\u201313 (written by [[Brian Michael Bendis]], [[Marvel Comics|Marvel]], 2002)\n* \"Memories of Green\" (in ''[[Marvel Knights]] Double Shot'' #2, [[Marvel Comics|Marvel]], 2002\n* ''[[Wonder Woman: The Blue Amazon]]'' (written by Randy & [[Jean-Marc Lofficier]], [[Elseworlds]] 2003)\n* \"A Life Less Empty\" (in ''[[The Matrix Comics]]'' #1, Burleyman, 2003)\n* \"The King of Never Return\" (in ''The Matrix Comics'' #2, Burleyman, 2004)\n* ''Enginehead'' #1\u20136 (written by [[Joe Kelly (comics)|Joe Kelly]], DC, 2004)\n* ''Little Book of Horror: War of the Worlds'' (written by [[Steve Niles]], [[IDW Publishing|IDW]], 2005)\n* \"Cuts\" (written by [[F. Paul Wilson]], in ''Doomed'', IDW, 2006)\n* ''[[The Nightmare Factory]]'' (graphic novel, [[Fox Atomic Comics]], 2007)\n* \"Past The Mission\" (in ''[[Comic Book Tattoo]]'', graphic novel, [[Image Comics]], 2008)\n* ''Meta4'' #1\u20135 ([[Image Comics]], 2010)\n* ''Mondo'' #1\u20133 ([[Image Comics]], 2012)\n* ''Miniature Jesus'' #1\u20135 ([[Image Comics]], 2013)\n* ''The Superannuated Man'' #1\u20136 ([[Image Comics]], 2014)\n* ''Pencil Head'' #1\u20135 ([[Image Comics]] , 2016)\n\n===Cover work===\nComics covers include:\n*''[[Nightbreed (comics)|Clive Barker's Night Breed]]'' #24\u201325 ([[Epic Comics|Epic]], 1993)\n*''[[Silent Hill (comics)|Silent Hill]]: Dead/Alive'' #1\u20135 (IDW, 2006) (variant covers only)\n*''[[Zombies! Feast]]'' #1\u20135 (IDW, 2006) (variant covers only)\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Refbegin}}\n*{{comicbookdb|type=creator|id=327|title=Ted McKeever}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McKeever, Ted}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:American comics artists]]\n[[Category:American comics writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American artists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American artists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American comic artist}}\n{{Infobox comics creator\n| name = Ted McKeever\n| image = \n| imagesize = 150\n| caption = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = [[United States|American]]\n| cartoonist = \n| write = y\n| art = \n| pencil = y\n| ink = y\n| edit = \n| publish = \n| letter = y\n| color = \n| alias = \n| notable works = {{ubl|''[[Plastic Forks]]''|''[[Metropol (comics)|Metropol]]''|''Perpetual Mourning'' (''[[Batman: Black & White]]'' #1)}}\n| awards = \n| website = {{official}}\n| sortkey = Mackeever, Ted\n| subcat = American\n}}\n'''Ted McKeever''' is an American [[comic]]s artist and author.\n\n==Career==\nMcKeever first professional work appeared in 1987, when he published the first five parts of his unfinished series ''Transit'' ([[Vortex Comics]]), establishing his trademark style. This was followed in 1987\u20131988 by his 12-part series ''[[Eddy Current (comics)|Eddy Current]]''. This \"12-hour book\" centers on an escapee from an asylum. Obsessed with the exploits of the superhero \"The Amazing Broccoli,\" Eddy buys a mail-order battery-powered \"Dynamic Fusion Suit\" and sets out to save the world. The work is quintessential McKeever: darkly humorous, showing an \"ordinary\" person caught up in extraordinary events. Some of the characters in Eddy Current reappear in ''Metropol'' and other later works, similarly from ''Transit''.  This series was nominated for the [[Eisner Award]]s for Best Single-Issue (#1), Best Black-and-White Series, Best New Series, and Best Artist (for McKeever) for 1988.\n\nHis five-parter ''Plastic Forks'' ([[Epic Comics|Epic]], 1990) explored the world of animal experimentation, albeit in a surreal and comical way.\n\n''Metropol'' ([[Epic Comics|Epic]] 1991\u20131992) is an epic story of the fight between angels and demons, but set in a modern  industrial landscape. An apocalyptic work in which non-entity Jasper Notochord becomes involved in a surreal fight between the forces of good and evil.\n\n''The Extremist'' ([[Vertigo Comics|Vertigo]], 1993), a four-parter written by [[Peter Milligan]], tells the tale of a woman who finds that her husband had a secret life, which she discovers upon his death. Her investigations lead her into a shocking world of extreme sex and violence.<ref name=\"vert-extr\">{{Citation  | last = Irvine | first = Alex | author-link = Alexander C. Irvine | contribution = The Extremist | editor-last = Dougall  | editor-first = Alastair  | title = The Vertigo Encyclopedia  | pages = 71 | publisher = [[Dorling Kindersley]]  | place = New York  | year = 2008 | ISBN = 0-7566-4122-5 | oclc = 213309015}}</ref>\n\nMcKeever has produced a number of works exploring alternative realities within the world of [[DC Comics|DC]] superhero comics. With Randy & [[Jean-Marc Lofficier]], he has produced an [[Elseworlds]] trilogy: ''[[Superman's Metropolis]]'', ''[[Batman: Nosferatu]]''\nand ''[[Wonder Woman: The Blue Amazon]]'', all retellings of the DC mythos.\n\nIn addition to Milligan and Randy & Jean-Marc Lofficier, McKeever has collaborated with comics creators [[Dave Gibbons]] and writer and singer [[Lydia Lunch]]. ''Enginehead'' (DC, 2004), was written by [[Joe Kelly (comics)|Joe Kelly]].\n\nIn 2010 McKeever worked on a five-part series titled \"Meta4\" for [[Image Comics]] where he has since published his recent projects for [[Jim Valentino]]'s Shadowline imprint.\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n* 1988 [[Eisner Award]]<ref name=\"awards-eisner-88\">{{Citation\n| last = Hahn\n| first = Joel\n| title = 1988 Will Eisner Comic Industry Award Nominees\n| url = http://www.hahnlibrary.net/comics/awards/eisner88.php\n| accessdate = 2008-10-19\n}}</ref>\n** Best Single Issue nominee: ''[[Eddy Current (comics)|Eddy Current]]'' #1\n** Best Black-and-White Series nominee: ''[[Eddy Current (comics)|Eddy Current]]''\n** Best New Series nominee: ''[[Eddy Current (comics)|Eddy Current]]''\n** Best Artist nominee: ''[[Eddy Current (comics)|Eddy Current]]''\n* 1991 [[Eisner Award]]<ref name=\"awards-eisner-91\">{{Citation\n| last = Hahn\n| first = Joel\n| title = 1991 Will Eisner Comic Industry Award Nominees and Winners\n| url = http://www.hahnlibrary.net/comics/awards/eisner91.php\n| accessdate = 2008-10-19\n}}</ref>\n** Best Artist nominee\n* 1992 Harvey Award<ref name=\"awards-harvey-92\">{{Citation\n| last = Hahn\n| first = Joel\n| title = 1992 Harvey Award Nominees and Winners\n| url = http://www.hahnlibrary.net/comics/awards/harvey92.php\n| accessdate = 2008-10-19\n}}</ref>\n** Best Colorist nominee: ''Metropol''\n* 1997 [[Eisner Award]]<ref name=\"awards-eisner-97\">{{Citation\n| last = Hahn\n| first = Joel\n| title = 1997 Will Eisner Comic Industry Award Nominees and Winners\n| url = http://www.hahnlibrary.net/comics/awards/eisner97.php\n| accessdate = 2008-10-19\n}}</ref>\n** Best Short Story nominee: ''Perpetual Mourning'', ''[[Batman: Black & White]]'' #1\n\n==Bibliography==\nComics written and drawn (unless noted otherwise) by Ted McKeever include:\n* ''Transit'' #1\u20135 ([[Vortex Comics|Vortex]], 1987\u20131988 \u2014 previously unfinished, but now completed in 2008 HC released by [[Shadowline]])\n* \"Eddy Current\" (''[[Eddy Current (comics)|Eddy Current]]'' prologue, in ''Splat!'' #3, ''Mad Dog Graphics'', 1987) \n* ''[[Eddy Current (comics)|Eddy Current]]'' #1\u201312 (''Mad Dog Graphics'', 1987\u20131988)\n* \"New Act\" (Eddy Current featured in Munden's Bar Back-up story, in ''[[Grimjack]]'' #47, [[First Comics]], 1988)\n* \"Judgement\" (''[[Eddy Current (comics)|Eddy Current]]'''s Nun short story, in ''[[Escape (magazine)|Escape]]'' #16, [[Titan Books]], 1988 \u2013 reprinted in ''[[A1 (comics)|A1]] [[The Bojeffries Saga|Bojeffries]] Terror Tome'' #1, [[Atomeka Press|Atomeka]], 2005)\n* \"Fish Sticks\" (written by [[Steve Moncuse]], in ''[[Fish Police]]'' vol. 2 #8, [[Comico: The Comic Company|Comico]], 1988)\n* \"Dance of The Fetus\" (in ''[[Hellraiser (comics)|Clive Barker's Hellraiser]]'' #1, [[Epic Comics|Epic]], 1989)\n* \"Libretto\" (art by [[Dave Gibbons]], in ''[[A1 (comics)|A1]] #1, [[Atomeka Press|Atomeka]], 1989)\n* \"Survivor\" (written by [[Dave Gibbons]], in ''[[A1 (comics)|A1]] #1, [[Atomeka Press|Atomeka]], 1989)\n* \"The Talk Of Creatures\" (in ''[[A1 (comics)|A1]] #2, [[Atomeka Press|Atomeka]], 1989)\n* ''Ted McKeever\u2019s [[Plastic Forks]]'' #1\u20135 ([[Epic Comics|Epic]], 1990)\n* ''[[Metropol (comics)|Metropol]]'' #1\u201312 ([[Epic Comics|Epic]], 1991\u20131992)\n* ''Metropol A.D.'' #1\u20133 ([[Epic Comics|Epic]], 1993)\n* ''[[Eclipso]]'' #7\u20138 (written by [[Keith Giffen]] and [[Robert Loren Fleming]], [[DC Comics|DC]], 1993)\n* ''[[The Extremist (comics)|The Extremist]]'' #1\u20134 (written by [[Peter Milligan]], [[Vertigo Comics|Vertigo]], 1993)\n* \"The Creeper: A Cold Night In Hell\" (written by [[Keith Giffen]], in ''Showcase '93'' #12, DC, 1993)\n* ''[[Doom Patrol]]'' #75\u201379, 81\u201382, 84\u201387 (written by [[Rachel Pollack]], [[Vertigo Comics|Vertigo]], 1994\u20131995)\n* ''[[Industrial Gothic]]'' #1\u20135 ([[Vertigo Comics|Vertigo]], 1995)\n* \"Engines\" (in ''[[Legends of the Dark Knight]]'' #74\u201375, DC, 1996)\n* \"Perpetual Mourning\" (in ''[[Batman: Black & White]]'' #1, DC, 1997)\n* ''[[Superman's Metropolis]]'' (written by Randy & [[Jean-Marc Lofficier]] & [[Roy Thomas]], [[Elseworlds]], 1997)\n* ''Junk Culture'' #1\u20132 (DC, 1997)\n* ''Toxic Gumbo'' (written by [[Lydia Lunch]], DC, 1998)\n* ''[[Batman: Nosferatu]]'' (written by Randy & [[Jean-Marc Lofficier]], [[Elseworlds]], 1999)\n* ''[[Faith (Vertigo)|Faith]]'' #1\u20135 ([[Vertigo Comics|Vertigo]], 2000)\n* \"Grave Wisdom\" (in ''[[Flinch (comics)|Flinch]]'' #14, [[Vertigo Comics|Vertigo]], 2000)\n* ''[[Vertigo Comics|Vertigo]] Visions'' ([[Titan Books]], 2000)\n* ''[[Spider-Man's Tangled Web]]'' #18 ([[Marvel Comics|Marvel]], 2002)\n* ''[[Ultimate Marvel Team-Up]]'' #12\u201313 (written by [[Brian Michael Bendis]], [[Marvel Comics|Marvel]], 2002)\n* \"Memories of Green\" (in ''[[Marvel Knights]] Double Shot'' #2, [[Marvel Comics|Marvel]], 2002\n* ''[[Wonder Woman: The Blue Amazon]]'' (written by Randy & [[Jean-Marc Lofficier]], [[Elseworlds]] 2003)\n* \"A Life Less Empty\" (in ''[[The Matrix Comics]]'' #1, Burleyman, 2003)\n* \"The King of Never Return\" (in ''The Matrix Comics'' #2, Burleyman, 2004)\n* ''Enginehead'' #1\u20136 (written by [[Joe Kelly (comics)|Joe Kelly]], DC, 2004)\n* ''Little Book of Horror: War of the Worlds'' (written by [[Steve Niles]], [[IDW Publishing|IDW]], 2005)\n* \"Cuts\" (written by [[F. Paul Wilson]], in ''Doomed'', IDW, 2006)\n* ''[[The Nightmare Factory]]'' (graphic novel, [[Fox Atomic Comics]], 2007)\n* \"Past The Mission\" (in ''[[Comic Book Tattoo]]'', graphic novel, [[Image Comics]], 2008)\n* ''Meta4'' #1\u20135 ([[Image Comics]], 2010)\n* ''Mondo'' #1\u20133 ([[Image Comics]], 2012)\n* ''Miniature Jesus'' #1\u20135 ([[Image Comics]], 2013)\n* ''The Superannuated Man'' #1\u20136 ([[Image Comics]], 2014)\n* ''Pencil Head'' #1\u20135 ([[Image Comics]] , 2016)\n\n===Cover work===\nComics covers include:\n*''[[Nightbreed (comics)|Clive Barker's Night Breed]]'' #24\u201325 ([[Epic Comics|Epic]], 1993)\n*''[[Silent Hill (comics)|Silent Hill]]: Dead/Alive'' #1\u20135 (IDW, 2006) (variant covers only)\n*''[[Zombies! Feast]]'' #1\u20135 (IDW, 2006) (variant covers only)\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Refbegin}}\n*{{comicbookdb|type=creator|id=327|title=Ted McKeever}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website}}\n\n{{Authority control|VIAF=44467626}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McKeever, Ted}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:American comics artists]]\n[[Category:American comics writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American artists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American artists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American writers]]\n", "name_user": "Vahurzpu", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:Move authority control to Wikidata", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ted_McKeever"}
{"title_page": "St Margaret's School for Girls", "text_new": "{{For|other schools of a similar name|St Margaret's School (disambiguation)}}\n{{distinguish|St Margaret's School, Edinburgh}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox UK school\n| name = St Margaret's School for Girls\n| image = St Margaret's School for Girls - geograph.org.uk - 1460003.jpg\n| motto = {{lang-fr|Tenez Ferme}}<br>(Hold Fast)\n| established = 1846\n| type = [[Independent school (UK)|Independent]] day school\n| head_label = Head\n| head = Anna Tomlinson\n| address = 17 Albyn Place\n| city = [[Aberdeen]]\n| country = Scotland\n| postcode = AB10 1RU\n| local_authority = [[Aberdeen City Council]]\n| dfeno = 528/2136\n| enrolment = 400+\n| gender = Girls\n| lower_age = 3\n| upper_age = 18\n| houses = Crathes, Dunnottar, Kildrummy\n| website = {{URL|http://www.st-margaret.aberdeen.sch.uk/|St Margaret's School for Girls}}\n}}\n'''St Margaret\u2019s School for Girls''' is the oldest all-through girls\u2019 school in Scotland it is meant to be good it is not! St Margaret\u2019s is an independent charitable trust that warmly welcomes girls of all denominations and faiths.\n\nSt Margaret's is a member of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), [[Girls' Schools Association]] and Queen Margaret of Scotland Girls' Schools Association.\n\n==History==\n\n=== Beginnings, 1846-1888 ===\nThe school was first established in 1846 by 21-year-old Ann Stephen as a day school for girls in the drawing room of her parents' house at 1 Union Wynd, where pupils were taught writing, music, sewing, French and German. After 10 years, the school moved to 13 Union Row, where it was extended to a 'day and boarding school'. Miss Stephen retired in 1874, and the school was taken over by two sisters, the Misses Reid, who ran it for just four years.\n\nIn 1878, Mary Andrew became headteacher, teaching French to the girls and insisting that they speak it at all meals and for certain hours in the evening; a fine was imposed on anyone who lapsed. According to the 1881 census, 13 boarders from the age of 11 to 19 lived at the school with Miss Andrew and a governess, a cook and a servant. Sadly, Miss Andrew died at the age of 40 in 1888.\n\n=== St Margaret's 1888-1929 ===\nSisters, Isabella and Jean Duncan, took over in 1888, moving the school to 31 Union Grove as it grew. Pupils were expected to dress with 'a sense of propriety', and an early photograph shows the girls wearing ankle-length skirts and long-sleeved white blouses. Spot checks on deportment and behaviour were made at the end of the school day to check that the girls were behaving in a seemly manner.\n\nIn May 1890, the school made its last move to 17 Albyn Place, where it remains today.\u00a0 A kindergarten class was established and the school was officially named St Margaret's School for Girls.\n\nThe \u2018best\u2019 rooms were the sitting room, with its veranda and stairs leading down to the back garden (the present headteacher\u2019s room), and the great drawing room (present library), with its vast bow-window, highly polished floor and gilt chairs.\n\nFollowing the sisters\u2019 retirement, the newly formed Council appointed Mary C. Bell as the first headteacher of the new independent St Margaret's. Electric lighting and a system of central heating were installed throughout, the big drawing-room was converted into a gymnasium and the assembly hall was turned into a library. The rooms where boarders had slept became classrooms and a staff room was established.\n\nMiss Bell introduced the prefect system, and founded the dramatic club and the debating society. She also started sports day and gymnastic and dancing displays. Two hockey pitches were rented, and tennis courts were borrowed from the Grammar School boarding house until 1926, when ground for two hockey pitches and two netball courts was acquired at King's Gate. Through gifts from Council, three tennis courts were laid out, and a sports pavilion was built. Miss Bell taught the girls of St Margaret's to think for themselves, to acquire a sense of responsibility and to have pride in their school.\n\n=== The School Well Established, 1929-1952 ===\nMiss Bell's successor was Mabel E. Holland and, under her able direction, the school rode out the problems of disruption and evacuation caused by the Second World War. Inheriting a school roll of 134, Miss Holland left with 365 pupils on the books. While maintaining the traditions and standards of the past, Miss Holland introduced new schemes, including a school magazine, ''The Chronicle,'' the building of a school hall, and the purchase of 15 Albyn Place. Meanwhile, the number of girls leaving school with the necessary qualification to attend university was growing steadily. The school hall was built and within a few months of the hall's opening, a passageway - known to this day as 'the pink passage' - was added to connect the new hall with the old school building. By March 1934, enough money had been raised to add extra rooms behind the hall, which doubled as green rooms for dramatic performances and as music practice rooms. The new building also allowed for the introduction of a Nursery Class. This was the first 'West-end' Nursery School in Aberdeen. Miss Holland also introduced the school uniform.\n\nHowever, the Second World War brought Miss Holland and her staff their greatest challenges. On her arrival at school in August 1939, with the new session due to start, Miss Holland was greeted by the news that 17 Albyn Place had been requisitioned for the Food Office.\n\n=== The Boarding Houses, 1856-1989 ===\nFor 133 years, pupils boarded at the school. As the numbers of boarders grew, the school acquired 7, and later No 6 Queen's Gardens. At the junior boarding house, Canmore House, the children were allowed to keep pets and each boarder had a small piece of garden.\n\nWith the coming of war in 1939, the boarding houses were evacuated to the country, for the greater safety of the children and because the school\u2019s buildings were requisitioned. Glenbuchat, 40 miles from Aberdeen on Upper Donside, was the first place of refuge. Here was remoteness indeed, especially for those in Glenbuchat Lodge, where the main road was seven miles away; a horse-drawn sledge was needed to deliver the groceries in the snowy winter of 1939.\n\nIn autumn 1947, (following the sale of the Queen's Gardens properties) the School Council purchased Culter House, which became home to many boarders for 41 years. However, as the number of boarders declined, the decision was taken to discontinue boarding and sell Culter House. After 133 years of boarding, St Margaret's was once more a day school.\n\n=== The post-war years onwards ===\nA long line of distinguished Heads have followed, along with many new improvements: a 'new look' uniform, a new telephone exchange, new lighting and nursery equipment were purchased, a new physics laboratory, a music room, and an improved gym. By 1983, a new six classroom junior block had been added, and in 1989, the Parents' Association was founded, along with the Pupil Council. An impressive new computing room was created and in 1996, St Margaret's built a music suite, a general purpose hall (the GP room), and two new classrooms. A new pavilion at the Summerhill playing fields was opened in 2009.\n\nIn 2015, the school completed its largest estate development in almost 20 years with the opening of its new state-of-the-art science block, which was officially opened by renowned British astrophysicist Dame Jocelyn Bell Burnell, who is credited with one of the most significant astronomical discoveries of the 20th century, that of radio pulsars. The new facility comprises four laboratories, a technician\u2019s room and a project room. Shortly after, new art and drama studios were also unveiled, significantly increasing the opportunity and space for pupils studying both discipline\n\n==The School's Crest and Motto==\nIn 1934, the school was granted by the Lord Lyon an achievement of arms. This consists of a shield bearing the arms of St Margaret, Queen of Scotland, surmounted by the three triple-towered castles which symbolise the City of Aberdeen. St Margaret's arms are 'a cross fleury' (a cross with fleurs-de-lys at its four ends) and five martels (heraldic swallows).\n\nThe motto below the shield is Tenez Ferme (hold fast), chosen at the suggestion of Dr Esslemont Adams, a member of the school's Council. The motto refers back to a story in the life of St Margaret. When she was riding pillion behind a seneschal they came to a boggy piece of ground and the seneschal cried out 'Haud siccar'. The Scots was translated into French when the motto was adopted officially as part of the school's coat of arms.\n\n==Academics==\nIn 2018, St Margaret\u2019s celebrated another year of excellent results. The pass rate at Advanced Higher was 96% (A-C grade), with 90% of grades awarded at A or B grade, while the pass rate was 95% at Higher level for S5 pupils (A-C grade), with 88% achieving A or B grade. Pupils in fourth year received a 98% pass rate at National 5, with 90% of candidates achieving at A or B level.\n\n==Houses==\nThe school operates three \u2018houses\u2019, all of which are named after local Scottish castles. Each pupil is allocated a house upon entering the school. They can win points for their house by completing various activities, competing in sports events and demonstrating an \u2018above and beyond\u2019 attitude with the aim of winning the House Shield at the end of the year.\n\nKildrummy: Kildrummy House is named after the great castle of Kildrummy, 35 miles west of Aberdeen, which, even in its ruined state, is a fine historic monument.\n\nCrathes: Crathes Castle, owned by the National Trust, was built by the Burnett family in 1553 and, unlike the other two castles that represent Houses in St Margaret\u2019s, is still standing intact today.\n\nDunnottar: Situated on the cliffs near Stonehaven, Dunnottar Castle is an impressive sight and is well worth a visit.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! House !! Colour\n|-\n| [[Crathes Castle|Crathes]] || {{colour box|red}}\n|-\n| [[Dunnottar Castle|Dunnottar]] || {{color box|green}}\n|-\n| [[Kildrummy Castle|Kildrummy]] || {{color box|blue}}\n|}\n<ref>[http://www.st-margaret.aberdeen.sch.uk/index.php/houses Houses]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.st-margaret.aberdeen.sch.uk/ School website]\n*[http://www.ltscotland.org.uk/scottishschoolsonline/schools/stmargaretsschoolforgirlsaberdeencity.asp St Margaret's School for Girls' page on Scottish Schools Online]\n*[[Her Majesty's Inspectorate of Education|HMIE]] Inspection [http://www.educationscotland.gov.uk/Images/StMargaretsSchoolforIns20050601_tcm4-693922.pdf Report]\n\n{{Secondary Schools of Aberdeen}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saint Margaret's School for Girls}}\n[[Category:Secondary schools in Aberdeen]]\n[[Category:Independent schools in Aberdeen]]\n[[Category:Girls' schools in Aberdeen]]\n[[Category:Member schools of the Girls' Schools Association]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|other schools of a similar name|St Margaret's School (disambiguation)}}\n{{distinguish|St Margaret's School, Edinburgh}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox UK school\n| name = St Margaret's School for Girls\n| image = St Margaret's School for Girls - geograph.org.uk - 1460003.jpg\n| motto = {{lang-fr|Tenez Ferme}}<br>(Hold Fast)\n| established = 1846\n| type = [[Independent school (UK)|Independent]] day school\n| head_label = Head\n| head = Anna Tomlinson\n| address = 17 Albyn Place\n| city = [[Aberdeen]]\n| country = Scotland\n| postcode = AB10 1RU\n| local_authority = [[Aberdeen City Council]]\n| dfeno = 528/2136\n| enrolment = 400+\n| gender = Girls\n| lower_age = 3\n| upper_age = 18\n| houses = Crathes, Dunnottar, Kildrummy\n| website = {{URL|http://www.st-margaret.aberdeen.sch.uk/|St Margaret's School for Girls}}\n}}\n'''St Margaret\u2019s School for Girls''' is the oldest all-through girls\u2019 school in Scotland and caters for pupils aged three to 18 in a nursery, junior school and senior school. St Margaret\u2019s is an independent charitable trust that warmly welcomes girls of all denominations and faiths.\n\nSt Margaret's is a member of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), [[Girls' Schools Association]] and Queen Margaret of Scotland Girls' Schools Association.\n\n==History==\n\n=== Beginnings, 1846-1888 ===\nThe school was first established in 1846 by 21-year-old Ann Stephen as a day school for girls in the drawing room of her parents' house at 1 Union Wynd, where pupils were taught writing, music, sewing, French and German. After 10 years, the school moved to 13 Union Row, where it was extended to a 'day and boarding school'. Miss Stephen retired in 1874, and the school was taken over by two sisters, the Misses Reid, who ran it for just four years.\n\nIn 1878, Mary Andrew became headteacher, teaching French to the girls and insisting that they speak it at all meals and for certain hours in the evening; a fine was imposed on anyone who lapsed. According to the 1881 census, 13 boarders from the age of 11 to 19 lived at the school with Miss Andrew and a governess, a cook and a servant. Sadly, Miss Andrew died at the age of 40 in 1888.\n\n=== St Margaret's 1888-1929 ===\nSisters, Isabella and Jean Duncan, took over in 1888, moving the school to 31 Union Grove as it grew. Pupils were expected to dress with 'a sense of propriety', and an early photograph shows the girls wearing ankle-length skirts and long-sleeved white blouses. Spot checks on deportment and behaviour were made at the end of the school day to check that the girls were behaving in a seemly manner.\n\nIn May 1890, the school made its last move to 17 Albyn Place, where it remains today.\u00a0 A kindergarten class was established and the school was officially named St Margaret's School for Girls.\n\nThe \u2018best\u2019 rooms were the sitting room, with its veranda and stairs leading down to the back garden (the present headteacher\u2019s room), and the great drawing room (present library), with its vast bow-window, highly polished floor and gilt chairs.\n\nFollowing the sisters\u2019 retirement, the newly formed Council appointed Mary C. Bell as the first headteacher of the new independent St Margaret's. Electric lighting and a system of central heating were installed throughout, the big drawing-room was converted into a gymnasium and the assembly hall was turned into a library. The rooms where boarders had slept became classrooms and a staff room was established.\n\nMiss Bell introduced the prefect system, and founded the dramatic club and the debating society. She also started sports day and gymnastic and dancing displays. Two hockey pitches were rented, and tennis courts were borrowed from the Grammar School boarding house until 1926, when ground for two hockey pitches and two netball courts was acquired at King's Gate. Through gifts from Council, three tennis courts were laid out, and a sports pavilion was built. Miss Bell taught the girls of St Margaret's to think for themselves, to acquire a sense of responsibility and to have pride in their school.\n\n=== The School Well Established, 1929-1952 ===\nMiss Bell's successor was Mabel E. Holland and, under her able direction, the school rode out the problems of disruption and evacuation caused by the Second World War. Inheriting a school roll of 134, Miss Holland left with 365 pupils on the books. While maintaining the traditions and standards of the past, Miss Holland introduced new schemes, including a school magazine, ''The Chronicle,'' the building of a school hall, and the purchase of 15 Albyn Place. Meanwhile, the number of girls leaving school with the necessary qualification to attend university was growing steadily. The school hall was built and within a few months of the hall's opening, a passageway - known to this day as 'the pink passage' - was added to connect the new hall with the old school building. By March 1934, enough money had been raised to add extra rooms behind the hall, which doubled as green rooms for dramatic performances and as music practice rooms. The new building also allowed for the introduction of a Nursery Class. This was the first 'West-end' Nursery School in Aberdeen. Miss Holland also introduced the school uniform.\n\nHowever, the Second World War brought Miss Holland and her staff their greatest challenges. On her arrival at school in August 1939, with the new session due to start, Miss Holland was greeted by the news that 17 Albyn Place had been requisitioned for the Food Office.\n\n=== The Boarding Houses, 1856-1989 ===\nFor 133 years, pupils boarded at the school. As the numbers of boarders grew, the school acquired 7, and later No 6 Queen's Gardens. At the junior boarding house, Canmore House, the children were allowed to keep pets and each boarder had a small piece of garden.\n\nWith the coming of war in 1939, the boarding houses were evacuated to the country, for the greater safety of the children and because the school\u2019s buildings were requisitioned. Glenbuchat, 40 miles from Aberdeen on Upper Donside, was the first place of refuge. Here was remoteness indeed, especially for those in Glenbuchat Lodge, where the main road was seven miles away; a horse-drawn sledge was needed to deliver the groceries in the snowy winter of 1939.\n\nIn autumn 1947, (following the sale of the Queen's Gardens properties) the School Council purchased Culter House, which became home to many boarders for 41 years. However, as the number of boarders declined, the decision was taken to discontinue boarding and sell Culter House. After 133 years of boarding, St Margaret's was once more a day school.\n\n=== The post-war years onwards ===\nA long line of distinguished Heads have followed, along with many new improvements: a 'new look' uniform, a new telephone exchange, new lighting and nursery equipment were purchased, a new physics laboratory, a music room, and an improved gym. By 1983, a new six classroom junior block had been added, and in 1989, the Parents' Association was founded, along with the Pupil Council. An impressive new computing room was created and in 1996, St Margaret's built a music suite, a general purpose hall (the GP room), and two new classrooms. A new pavilion at the Summerhill playing fields was opened in 2009.\n\nIn 2015, the school completed its largest estate development in almost 20 years with the opening of its new state-of-the-art science block, which was officially opened by renowned British astrophysicist Dame Jocelyn Bell Burnell, who is credited with one of the most significant astronomical discoveries of the 20th century, that of radio pulsars. The new facility comprises four laboratories, a technician\u2019s room and a project room. Shortly after, new art and drama studios were also unveiled, significantly increasing the opportunity and space for pupils studying both discipline\n\n==The School's Crest and Motto==\nIn 1934, the school was granted by the Lord Lyon an achievement of arms. This consists of a shield bearing the arms of St Margaret, Queen of Scotland, surmounted by the three triple-towered castles which symbolise the City of Aberdeen. St Margaret's arms are 'a cross fleury' (a cross with fleurs-de-lys at its four ends) and five martels (heraldic swallows).\n\nThe motto below the shield is Tenez Ferme (hold fast), chosen at the suggestion of Dr Esslemont Adams, a member of the school's Council. The motto refers back to a story in the life of St Margaret. When she was riding pillion behind a seneschal they came to a boggy piece of ground and the seneschal cried out 'Haud siccar'. The Scots was translated into French when the motto was adopted officially as part of the school's coat of arms.\n\n==Academics==\nIn 2018, St Margaret\u2019s celebrated another year of excellent results. The pass rate at Advanced Higher was 96% (A-C grade), with 90% of grades awarded at A or B grade, while the pass rate was 95% at Higher level for S5 pupils (A-C grade), with 88% achieving A or B grade. Pupils in fourth year received a 98% pass rate at National 5, with 90% of candidates achieving at A or B level.\n\n==Houses==\nThe school operates three \u2018houses\u2019, all of which are named after local Scottish castles. Each pupil is allocated a house upon entering the school. They can win points for their house by completing various activities, competing in sports events and demonstrating an \u2018above and beyond\u2019 attitude with the aim of winning the House Shield at the end of the year.\n\nKildrummy: Kildrummy House is named after the great castle of Kildrummy, 35 miles west of Aberdeen, which, even in its ruined state, is a fine historic monument.\n\nCrathes: Crathes Castle, owned by the National Trust, was built by the Burnett family in 1553 and, unlike the other two castles that represent Houses in St Margaret\u2019s, is still standing intact today.\n\nDunnottar: Situated on the cliffs near Stonehaven, Dunnottar Castle is an impressive sight and is well worth a visit.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! House !! Colour\n|-\n| [[Crathes Castle|Crathes]] || {{colour box|red}}\n|-\n| [[Dunnottar Castle|Dunnottar]] || {{color box|green}}\n|-\n| [[Kildrummy Castle|Kildrummy]] || {{color box|blue}}\n|}\n<ref>[http://www.st-margaret.aberdeen.sch.uk/index.php/houses Houses]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.st-margaret.aberdeen.sch.uk/ School website]\n*[http://www.ltscotland.org.uk/scottishschoolsonline/schools/stmargaretsschoolforgirlsaberdeencity.asp St Margaret's School for Girls' page on Scottish Schools Online]\n*[[Her Majesty's Inspectorate of Education|HMIE]] Inspection [http://www.educationscotland.gov.uk/Images/StMargaretsSchoolforIns20050601_tcm4-693922.pdf Report]\n\n{{Secondary Schools of Aberdeen}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saint Margaret's School for Girls}}\n[[Category:Secondary schools in Aberdeen]]\n[[Category:Independent schools in Aberdeen]]\n[[Category:Girls' schools in Aberdeen]]\n[[Category:Member schools of the Girls' Schools Association]]\n", "name_user": "Lindbarzrcool", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/St_Margaret%27s_School_for_Girls"}
